# Import data from my GitHub Page
# url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/truongphanduykhanh/Loan-Default-Prediction/master/prosperLoanData.csv"
url = 'prosperLoanData.csv'
loan = pd.read_csv(url)

# choose relevant columns based on financial expertise
loan = loan[["LoanStatus", "CreditGrade", "Term", "BorrowerAPR", "ProsperScore", 
             "BorrowerState", "EmploymentStatus", "EmploymentStatusDuration", "IsBorrowerHomeowner", 
             "CreditScoreRangeLower", "CreditScoreRangeUpper", "OpenCreditLines", 
             "DelinquenciesLast7Years", "PublicRecordsLast12Months", "RevolvingCreditBalance", 
             "AvailableBankcardCredit", "DebtToIncomeRatio", "IncomeRange", "TotalProsperLoans", 
             "TotalProsperPaymentsBilled", "ProsperPaymentsLessThanOneMonthLate", "ProsperPaymentsOneMonthPlusLate", 
             "ProsperPrincipalBorrowed", "ScorexChangeAtTimeOfListing", "LoanOriginalAmount", "Recommendations",
             "InvestmentFromFriendsAmount"]]

# There are some variables in the dataset that are available only after a loan is determined Defaulted or Completed
# such as "LoanCurrentDaysDelinquent" and "AmountDelinquent". In fact, if we incoporate these variables into statistical models,
# We will obtain even 100% of accurary. However, it's non-sense to use these features to predict if a loan is defaulted.

# filter only loans whose status are determined (either 'Completed' or 'Defaulted')
loan = loan.loc[loan.LoanStatus.isin(['Completed', 'Defaulted'])]

# Encode the columns "IncomeRange" and "LoanStatus"
cleanup_nums = {"IncomeRange": {"$25,000-49,999": np.mean([25000, 49999]),
                                "$50,000-74,999": np.mean([50000, 74999]),
                                "$75,000-99,999": np.mean([75000, 99999]),
                                "$1-24,999": np.mean([1, 24999]),
                                '$100,000+': 125000,
                                "$0": 0,
                                "Not employed": 0,
                                "Not displayed": np.nan},
                
                "LoanStatus": {"Completed": 0,
                               "Defaulted": 1}
               }

loan.replace(cleanup_nums, inplace=True)

# Encode the columns 'CreditScoreRangeLower' and 'CreditScoreRangeUpper'
loan['CreditScore'] = (loan['CreditScoreRangeLower'] + loan['CreditScoreRangeUpper'])/2
loan.drop(['CreditScoreRangeLower', 'CreditScoreRangeUpper'], axis=1, inplace=True)


loan.rename(columns={'LoanStatus':'Defaulted'}, inplace=True)

Impute missing value¶

In [5]:
# Impute missing value in categorical columns by 'Unknown'
cat_col = ['BorrowerState', 'EmploymentStatus', 'IsBorrowerHomeowner']
loan[cat_col] = loan[cat_col].fillna('Unknown')
loan[cat_col] = loan[cat_col].astype('category')

# Impute missing value in numeric columns by the means
loan.loc[:, loan.columns[~loan.columns.isin(cat_col)]] = loan.loc[:, loan.columns[~loan.columns.isin(cat_col)]].fillna(loan.mean())

print('The shape of final data is {}'.format(loan.shape))

There is a need of converting those categorical variables into dummies. For EmploymentStatus: It's faily surprised that Full-time job clients have higher Defaulted Rate compared to Not employed and Part-time. Nevertheless, we group Self-employed, Full-time, Retired and Other into one group. Not employed, Part-time and Employed to the other group.

For BorrowerState: Since there are nearly 5000 loans applied in California, we create a single group for CA. All other states which have lower Defaulted Rate than CA will be grouped together. Similarly, all the states which have higher Defaulted Rate will join in one cluster.

# Convert categorical variables in to dummies

# EmploymentStatus_0 = 1 if EmploymentStatus in ['Not employed', 'Part-time', 'Employed'], 0 otherwise
loan['EmploymentStatus_0'] = [int(x in ['Not employed', 'Part-time', 'Employed']) for x in loan['EmploymentStatus']]
loan = loan.drop(['EmploymentStatus'], axis=1)


# BorrowerState_CA = 1 if BorrowerState='CA' 
# BorrowerState_0 = 1 if BorrowerState are those whose Defaulted Rate < Defaulted Rate of 'CA'
# BorrowerState_1 = 1 if BorrowerState are those whose Defaulted Rate > Defaulted Rate of 'CA'
BorrowerState_0 = BorrowerState.index[BorrowerState['DefaultedRate'] < BorrowerState.loc['CA', 'DefaultedRate']]
loan['BorrowerState_0'] = [int(x in BorrowerState_0) for x in loan['BorrowerState']]
loan['BorrowerState_CA'] = [int(x == 'CA') for x in loan['BorrowerState']]
loan = loan.drop(['BorrowerState'], axis=1)


# IsBorrowerHomeowner = 1 if IsBorrowerHomeowner='True' 
loan['IsBorrowerHomeowner'] = loan['IsBorrowerHomeowner'].astype('bool').astype('int')

The heat map of correlation matrix gives a hint to determine important variables. A variable which is highly correlated to "Defaulted", either negatively or positively, can be the key feature to distinguish Defaulted loans from non-Defaulted ones. Particularly, BorrowerAPR, DebtToIncomeRatio and CreditScore are the most correlated aspects to Defaulted loans.

Moreover, the heat map also allows us to detect redundant variables, if any, when the correlation between any two variables approaches 1 or -1. The maximum absolute correlation values in our case is nearly 0.5 which is not extremely high, therefore we can keep all the variables for the statistical models.

PCA (Principal component analysis) plane depicts some extreme values in the data set. It doesn't, however, separate well the group Defaulted and Not Defaulted. Theoretically, it's completely understandable because PCA only tries to represent the most variation of the data regardless the observations’ labels. Moreover, the above PCA plane explains only 25% variation of the data.

On the other hand, rather than stretching the overall variation, t-SNE (t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding) - a fairly recent method to reduce dimensions of data, tries to maximize the local variation. Nonetheless, it is not able to tell which part of the plane contains more Defaulted Loans. The heavily overlapping of labels in PCA and t-SNE may be a signal of difficulty in training the predictive models.

Define score function for tuning parameters¶

It is very important to note that there is a tremendous difference between False Negative (FN) and False Positive (FP) predictions in our problem. An actual defaulted loan predicted as non-defaulted (FN) may lead to a big loss for the company. On the other hand, a non-defaulted loan predicted as defaulted (FP), i.e. do not process the good loan, would only take a small potential interest away. Therefore, we put more weight on defaulted loans so that we minimize FN given an acceptable level of FP.

The weight may vary from one company to another. In this problem, we assume one defaulted loan causes a loss which is approximately equal to 20 completed loans. Therefore, we set the weight to be 1:20, i.e. roughly speaking 1 FN is as bad as 20 FP.

In [19]:
class_weight = {0:1, 1:20}
In [20]:
# Following the class_weight, we define the score function in order to obtain the best model in term of this metric
# In fact, the metric is based on F1 Measure (F1 Score) with addition of class_weight

def f1_custom(y_true, y_pred, class_weight = {0:1, 1:20}):
    
    weight = class_weight[1]/class_weight[0]
    
    TP = sum([x==(1, 1) for x in zip(y_true, y_pred)]) # true positive
    FN = sum([x==(1, 0) for x in zip(y_true, y_pred)]) # false negative
    FP = sum([x==(0, 1) for x in zip(y_true, y_pred)]) # false positive
    TN = sum([x==(0, 0) for x in zip(y_true, y_pred)]) # true negative
       
    precision = TP*weight / (TP*weight + FP)
    recall = TP*weight / (TP*weight + FN*weight)
    f1_custom = 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)
    
    return f1_custom

f1_custom = make_scorer(f1_custom, greater_is_better=True) # convert the function into scorer

# Set up models:

# Logistic regression
logit = LogisticRegression(random_state=42, solver='liblinear', multi_class='ovr', class_weight=class_weight)
logit_grid = GridSearchCV(logit,
                          param_grid={'penalty': ['l1', 'l2'],
                                      'tol': [1e-1, 1e-2, 1e-3],
                                      'C': np.logspace(-2, 2, 5)},
                          scoring=f1_custom,
                          return_train_score=True,
                          cv=5)

# Support vector machine
svm = SVC(random_state=42, gamma='auto', kernel='linear', class_weight=class_weight)
svm_grid = GridSearchCV(svm,
                        param_grid={'tol': [1e-2, 1e-3, 1e-4],
                                    'C': np.logspace(-1, 1, 3)},
                        scoring=f1_custom,
                        return_train_score=True,
                        cv=5)

# Random forest
forest = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, criterion='gini', class_weight=class_weight)
forest_grid = GridSearchCV(forest,
                           param_grid={'n_estimators': [30, 50, 100],
                                       'min_impurity_decrease': np.logspace(-7, -2, 6)},
                           scoring=f1_custom,
                           return_train_score=True,
                           cv=5)

# Define a function that show the value on top of columns in barplot of Searborn

def add_value_labels(ax, spacing=0, formating="{:.1%}"):
    """Add labels to the end of each bar in a bar chart.

    Arguments:
        ax (matplotlib.axes.Axes): The matplotlib object containing the axes
            of the plot to annotate.
        spacing (int): The distance between the labels and the bars.
    """

    # For each bar: Place a label
    for rect in ax.patches:
        # Get X and Y placement of label from rect.
        y_value = rect.get_height()
        x_value = rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2

        # Number of points between bar and label. Change to your liking.
        space = spacing
        # Vertical alignment for positive values
        va = 'bottom'

        # If value of bar is negative: Place label below bar
        if y_value < 0:
            # Invert space to place label below
            space *= -1
            # Vertically align label at top
            va = 'top'

        # Use Y value as label and format number with one decimal place
        label = formating.format(y_value)

        # Create annotation
        ax.annotate(
            label,                      # Use `label` as label
            (x_value, y_value),         # Place label at end of the bar
            xytext=(0, space),          # Vertically shift label by `space`
            textcoords="offset points", # Interpret `xytext` as offset in points
            ha='center',                # Horizontally center label
            va=va)                      # Vertically align label differently for
                                        # positive and negative values.

test_score_svm = np.max(svm_grid.cv_results_['mean_test_score'])
test_score_forest = np.max(forest_grid.cv_results_['mean_test_score'])

train_score_logit = logit_grid.cv_results_['mean_train_score'][np.argmax(logit_grid.cv_results_['mean_test_score'])]
train_score_svm = svm_grid.cv_results_['mean_train_score'][np.argmax(svm_grid.cv_results_['mean_test_score'])]
train_score_forest = forest_grid.cv_results_['mean_train_score'][np.argmax(forest_grid.cv_results_['mean_test_score'])]

score_cv = pd.DataFrame({'Model': ['Logit', 'SVM', 'Forest'],
                         'Train': [train_score_logit, train_score_svm, train_score_forest],
                         'Test': [test_score_logit, test_score_svm, test_score_forest]})

score_cv = pd.melt(score_cv, id_vars="Model", var_name="Type", value_name='Score')
In [25]:
# Display the best mean_test_score and corresponding mean_train_score from GridSearchCV

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))

ax = sns.barplot(x='Model',
                 y='Score',
                 hue='Type',
                 data=score_cv)
plt.title('Mean Cross-Validated Custom F1 Score', size=15)
plt.xlabel(None)
add_value_labels(ax, spacing=0)
plt.ylim(0, 1.1);

The average (custom) F1 score on test set from cross validation of Random Forest and Support Vector Machine are the highest among the three models with 81.9% and 81.5%, respectively. Logistic Regression follows just behind with 80.8%. At each model, the score on test set is just a little lower than on the train set. This fact depicts that our three models do not suffer from over-fitting problem.

Note that we have split the original data set into training set (used for cross validation training) and testing set. Although SVM and Random Forest seem to be less accurate, these two models make fewer False Positive (Predicted 1, Actual 0) predictions.

People may claim that the performance of three models are very poor if they look at the F1 score and especially at the above confusion matrix. The majority of the predictions are False Positive. This is because we have discussed earlier that we have set the class weight 1:20 for non-Defaulted and Defaulted labels, respectively. As a result, the models are very conservative to make False Negative predictions (Predicted 0, Actual 1). If we haven't set the sample weight (class weight is 1:1 as origin), the F1 score and confusion matrix would have been much more 'beautiful' but there would be a lot more False Negative predictions.

Feature Importance¶

In [33]:
# Meaningful variables 

importance = pd.DataFrame([X_train.columns,
                           abs(logit_grid.best_estimator_.coef_[0]), # coefficients of logit model
                           abs(svm_grid.best_estimator_.coef_[0]), # coefficients of SVM
                           forest_grid.best_estimator_.feature_importances_]).transpose() # feature importance in random forest

importance.columns = ['Variable', 'Logit', 'SVM', 'Random Forest']
importance.sort_values('Random Forest', ascending=False, inplace=True)

# Plot the feature importances of the forest
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 5))
plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
sns.barplot(x='Variable',
            y='Logit',
            data=importance)

plt.xticks(rotation=90, size=12)
plt.xlabel(None)
plt.ylabel(None)
plt.title('Logit\nImporance of Feature', size=15);


plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
sns.barplot(x='Variable',
            y='SVM',
            data=importance)

plt.xticks(rotation=90, size=12)
plt.xlabel(None)
plt.ylabel(None)
plt.title('SVM\nImporance of Feature', size=15);


plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
sns.barplot(x='Variable',
            y='Random Forest',
            data=importance)

plt.xticks(rotation=90, size=12)
plt.xlabel(None)
plt.ylabel(None)
plt.title('Random Forest\nImporance of Feature', size=15);

Because the data is normalized so that every feature has identical standard deviation, the absolute size of coefficients in Logit and SVM can be used as the measurement of feature importance (this was absolutely not true if the data was not scaled). Moreover, the feature importance of Random Forest is not sensitive to the scaled data, i.e. scaled and non-scaled data will theoretically generate the same result in Random Forest.

As result, "BorrowerAPR", "DebtToIncomeRatio", "EmploymentStatus_0" and "CreditScore" are the most critical information to detect if a loan is Defaulted.

Conclusion ===============================================================¶

We have employed three models Logit, SVM and Random Forest to classify Defaulted Loans of Prosper Funding. All three models perform fairly similar with the custom F1 score approximately 80%. It is immensely essential to note that scoring in financial industry (peer-to-peer lending or banking) should be more sensitive to make False Negative predictions. The setting of the class weight will help overcome the problem.
